    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="316"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/376: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Shanghai Chinese General Chamber of
                            Commerce and the Shanghai Foreign General Chamber of Commerce</gloss> to
                        the Chinese Minister</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sze</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="10" xml:id="d316fn10">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Chinese Chargé under covering letter of March 6.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-05">March 5 (?),
                            1934</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Kindly forward the following message to His Excellency President Roosevelt.</p>
                <p>We jointly desire respectfully to endorse views telegraphed by Chinese Bankers
                    Association deprecating artificial measures to raise the price of silver. We are
                    convinced that a rise in the price of silver unless accompanied by a
                    corresponding rise in all commodity prices would be likely to produce most
                    harmful reaction in China.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai Chinese General Chamber of Commerce</hi>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai Foreign General Chamber of Commerce</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
